Ears
Do all animals have similar ears?
! Animals have special sense of hearing. It is one of their defenses against 
dang er. They listen carefully to the sounds around them and if they feel that 
they are in dang er, they alert the other animals of the group.
! Bats and dolphins use their sense of hearing to see in the dark. They mak e 
sounds which bounce off objects to guide them on their course.
Environmental Studies-421Unit–II : The Living World

You  Know Must ! Elephan ts use their huge fan-lik e ears to cool 
their body .
The sense of hearing of mos t animals is better than that of humans. It is belie ved 
that some animals like elephan ts can hear storms, earthquak es and other natural 
disas ters before humans can.Some animals have hearing organs in different parts of their bodies.
! Cicadas and crick ets have their hearing organs in their 
knees.
! Male mosquitoes hear with thousands of tiny hair 
growing on their antennae.
! Fishes have ears in their head.
! Birds do not have any outer ears but just two holes in the 
head.
Some birds have very sharp sense of hearing. They can hear a fish 
jump in the ocean while flying high in the sky.
Fur and Hair
Animals have hair on their head and other parts of 
their body . Some animals have hair covering all 
parts of their body while some have very little hair. 
Animals living in cold regions e.g. yak and polar 
bear have thick fur that covers all parts of their 
bodies. The fur traps air and keeps the body warm.
(Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-4 22

! Animals like camels which live in warm areas, have 
thick skin and very little hair on their bodies.
The different patterns on the animals are also due to the hair on their skin. The 
leopar d has spots on its body . Tigers have a striped coat. This help s them to hide in 
the bushes while chasing their prey.
Animals’ furs are useful to humans as well. We use fur of rabbit and wool of sheep 
to mak e warm clothing.
! Animals like cat and fox have fine and closely spaced 
hair on their body . It is called fur.
! A sheep has soft and matted coats of hair which is 
called wool.
! Monk eys have stiff hair that are called bristles.
! Hedgehogs and porcupines have 
pointed bristles which are called 
spines .
! Hair on the body of birds are called feathers. 
Feathers keep them warm and help them to fly.

Governmen t of India has put a ban on killing animals for skin, fur, nails or

Animals in Groups
Man y animals live together in groups. Large groups of animals are often called 
herds. They live in groups due to various reasons such as–
! To protect themselv es from enemies.
! To raise their young ones.
! To get food easily .
! To enjo y each other's compan y.
! To keep themselv es warm.
Animals groups are led by a leader who is strong 
and dominating. The leader takes the major 
decisions and leads the group.
Cows, buffaloes, horses, elephan ts, zebras and 
deer are some animals that live in groups. Each 
group is called a herd.
In an elephan t herd, 10 or more female elephan ts 
and their calves live together. The oldes t female in 
the herd leads the groups. The male elephan t lives 
with the group for some years and then moves 
away.
Lions live in groups called prides. Ther e are usually 
two males, six females and cubs in a pride. The 
lionesses do majority of the hunting for their 
pride. Both male and female defend their pride 
from enemies.
(Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-4 24

A group of monk eys is called a troop. A troop of 
monkeys usually has many male and female 
member s with their childr en.
A groups of birds is called a flock. By moving in a 
group, birds are able to keep safe and find food 
easily . Flying in a flock help s in reducing the ener gy 
needed to fly over long distances.
A groups of wolves is known as a pack. A pack 
usually has a male wolf, a female wolf and their 
childr en.
A group of bees is called a  swarm. Bees exist as a 
social unit. They mak e a beehiv e to live in. In the 
beehiv e lives a queen bee, thousands of worker 
bees and a few hundr ed male bees called drones.
Fish live in a group called school.
A large group of ants is called a colon y.
Behaviour of Animals
Shy Animals–  Ther e are man y animals that avoid human beings. When they see 
people coming towards them, they feel shy and run away. Squirr els, mice, birds, 
lizards are all shy. Tortoise and rabbit are also shy.
Friendly Animals–  Some animals are friendly by nature. If you give them food 
they will immedia tely come forward to eat it. Pigeons, cows, dogs and goats are 
gener ally friendly by nature. Hens and duck s are also friendly animals. Dolphins are 
friendly sea creatures.

They turn aggressiv e on seeing humans. Mos t of the aggressiv e animals are 
carniv orous or omniv orous.

Let’sKNOW Let’sKNOWStarterBirds : Beaks and Claws4
Birds are the flying beauties. Their body is covered with feathers. They have 
wings which help them to fly. However, some birds like penguins, kiwis, emus 
and ostriches cannot fly.
Birds do not have any teeth to bite, cut or chew their food like other animals. 
They have a hard and horn y part on the mouth. It is called the beak. Different 
birds have different beak s. The shape and size of beak s depends on the kind of 
food they eat.! Are the mouth, t eeth and f eet of all animals similar?

Kinds of Beaks
Short, hard and horn y beak s– Birds like sparr ow, pigeon, hen and dove mos tly eat 
seeds and grains. They have short, hard and horn y beak s to break their food before 
eating.
Sparrow Pigeon Hen Dove 
Environmental Studies-4 30
Unit–II : The Living World

Hook ed Beak s– Some birds like parrot which need to crack open nuts and seeds 
from fruits, have a poin ted and hook ed beak. Birds like vultur es, eagles and owls 
and kites are mea t-eaters. They also have sharp hook ed beak s which help them to 
tear flesh.
Vulture Eagle Owl Kite
Chisel-shaped Beak s– Some birds like wrens and woodpeck ers have a long chisel-
shaped beak. They use their beak s to drill into the wood to look for insects.
Wren Woodpecker
Broad and flat Beak s– Birds like duck and swan dig up the mud under water for 
their food. They have flat and broad beak s which have strainer s all along the edges. 
When the y squee ze the beak, w ater and mud g o out thr ough these s trainer s and 
the food remains inside the mouth.
Straw shaped Beak–  Humming birds have a long 
and slender beak. It help s them to suck nect ar from 
flowers.Humming bird 
Environmental Studies-431
Duck Swan

You  Know Must Spear -Shaped Beak–  Birds like pelic an, kingfisher and heron have a spear -shaped 
beak, which help s them to pierce into a fish and lift it out of water.
Pelican Kingfisher Heron 
Some birds like the tailor bird and weaver bird have special beak s that can weave or 
sew leaves, straw etc. to mak e their nests.
Study o f birds is known as ornithology.
Toes and Claws
Birds have two feet with usually four toes each, with sharp nails called claws. They 
uses them to hold the branches of trees, to catch their food, to swim or move 
around. They also use their toes and claws to protect themselv es from enemies, for 
fighting, for climbing up the tree trunk s and for scratching the ground.
Different birds have different claws according to their needs.
Scratching Birds– Birds like hen and quail use their feet 
for scratching the ground to bring out the burried 
seeds, insects and worms. The claws of these birds 
have three strong toes with sharp nails in front and one 
short toe at the back.Hunter Birds– Flesh eating birds like eagle, hawk and 
kite have strong and sharp claws to catch and hold 
their prey firmly .(Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-4 32

You  Know Must Perching Birds– Birds like crow, sparr ow and mynah 
spend mos t of their life on trees. The have three slender 
toes in front and one at the back. These help the birds to 
hold on to the branches firmly . These birds do not fall off 
even while sleeping. This type of gripping is called 
perching. So, these birds are known as perching birds.
Climbing Birds– Birds like woodpeck er and parrot are 
called climbing birds. They have two toes which poin t 
upwards and two other s which poin t downwards. These 
help them to climb and cling to trees.
Swimming Birds– Swimming birds like duck and swan 
have webbed feet. They have three toes in front and one 
at the back. The three front toes are joined by flaps of 
skin called webs. These help them to use their feet while 
swimming.
Wading Birds– Birds like crane, heron, stork etc. have 
long legs with spread out toes. This help s them to wade 
through muddy water to catch fish.
Some birds like the three-toed woodpeck er have three toes, 
while the ostrich have only two toes.Sparrow toes
